Despite attempts at a settlement, no damages were awarded. The judge ordered the withdrawal of Madonna's " Ray of Light discs in Belgium and banned further airing of "Frozen". A second case of plagiarism was brought against both Madonna and Salvatore by Italian composer Edouard Scotto Di Suoccio for their song "Blood Night". In 2014, a Belgian court overturned the original plagiarism verdict, ending an eight-year ban on the song in Belgium, this occurred following comparison of all 3 songs, and that they were "not sufficiently 'original' to claim" there was any plagiarism taking place.

name: You Are My Sunshine
comments: The real author of this song will probably stay unknown forever. There are at least four theories about it: 1) Paul Rice wrote it in 1937, inspired by a letter from a fan, and sold his rights to Jimmie Davis and Charles Mitchell in 1940. Some time later, Mitchell sold his share to Davis. This story is the most trustworthy. 2) Jimmie Davis wrote it in the early twenties. This version is unprovable. 3) An unknown lady singer from South Carolina wrote the song and offered it to the Pine Ridge Boys. Another unconfirmed story, but at least it would explain why they were the first to record it. 4) According to Prof. Toru Mitsui (Kanazawa University), the song was written in 1933 by Oliver Hood. Although the source is very authoritative, also this theory cannot be proven for certain. When it was copyrighted in 1940 it was attributed to Jimmie Davis and Charles Mitchell . Currently, only Davis is registered as the composer and author of the song.

name: Can't Get the One I Want
Fair Margaret and Sweet William
comments: Traditional English folk song. The earliest known fragments can be found in Francis Beaumont and John Fletcher's play "The Knight of the Burning Pestle" (1611). The song is in the Percy Folio and is Child Ballad no. 74. It also has a strong Appalachian heritage:  it's recorded in Cecil Sharp and Maud Karpeles, "English Folk Songs from the Southern Appalachians" (no. 20). Related English ballads which share stanza composition as well as narratives of heartbreak-induced death include Lord Thomas and Fair Annet / Eleanor and Lord Lovel.

name: Sea of Love
comments: Phil Phillips claimed for many years that label owner George Khoury was not a co-writer of "Sea Of Love". In those days it was standard practice for label owners to give themselves composer credits. Phillips took the matter to court several times in the 1980s and 1990s when other people were coming out with hit cover versions. Unfortunately Khoury's Kamar Music had by then been taken over by the powerful Trio/Fort Knox publishing empire making it hard for a little guy from Louisiana to win. See here for some details.

name: Adagio
comments: Full title: "Adagio in sol minore per archi e organo, su due spunti tematici e su un basso numerato di Tomaso Albinoni." Remo Giazotto, musicologist and Albinoni biographer, claimed to have obtained a fragment of a sonata (or a concerto) for strings and organ from the Saxon State Library in Dresden. Only the bass line and six bars of melody had survived. Giazotto never produced the fragment and no record of its presence has been found in the collection of the Saxon State Library. At one point, Giazotto himself claimed full credit for the work. Since his death in 1998, "Albinoni's Adagio" is commonly attributed solely to Giazotto.

name: Groupie (Superstar)
comments: The song started with an idea by Rita Coolidge. who came up with the idea for a song about "groupies". She took the idea to Leon Russell, who was a guitarist and keyboardist with Delaney and Bramlett and Friends at the time. Russell brought the raw material to Bonnie Bramlett, and together they began shaping it into a song. Coolidge sat and sang harmony as they wrote the song, but never asked for a writing credit. Several artists, including Cher, Coolidge herself and Bette Midler, all performed the song, but it was the Carpenters version that made the song a hit. Richard Carpenter got the idea of the cover after watching Midler perform it on The Tonight Show with Johnny Carson.

name: Away in a Manger [Mueller]
comments: The widest known version of the song uses Murray's tune and lyrics, as well as the third stanza, first appeared in the 1892 Gabriel's version. This version is also known as "Mueller", after a mysterious composer called Carl Mueller. To date, nothing has been found about his identity and his role in the composition. Nevertheless, there are several documents (especially from the 1920's and 1930's) that mention the song as credited to Martin Luther (lyrics) and Carl Mueller (music). It is likely that the false attribution to a "German" composer should serve as a sort of proof that the song came from Germany, where the Lutheranism was born. Note that in the UK the lyrics are usually set to the tune "Cradle Song", written in 1895 by William J. Kirkpatrick.
adapted_from: Cradle Song written by Charles H. Gabriel

name: I Get Along Without You Very Well
comments: When Carmichael was still in school at the University of Indiana, a friend had seen the poem "Except Sometimes" in "Life" and had clipped it out and passed it along. A few years later, after reworking the lyrics and melody a couple more times, Carmichael was ready to set the song in stone. But he had a problem: to publish a song with lyrics based so obviously on a pre-existing work by someone else, he’d have to acquire the permission of that person. Carmichael made a national plea for the author to step forward, even enlisting the help of top newspaper columnist and radio personality Walter Winchell, but only impostors turned up. Finally, the author was located in Philadelphia – Mrs Jane Brown Thompson.
adapted_from: Except Sometimes written by Jane Brown Thompson
